The paper discusses an algorithm for on-line feature extraction for an intelligent agent to adapt its representation to the requirements of its task as it interacts with the world. This falls under the broad category of machine learning and artificial intelligence. The paper specifically mentions the use of Q-learning, which is a popular reinforcement learning algorithm used in robotics and control systems, indicating that the paper may belong to the sub-category of robotics (cs.RO). The paper also mentions the partitioning of continuous state-spaces, which is a common technique in neural networks and deep learning, indicating that the paper may belong to the sub-category of neural networks (cs.NE). The paper's focus on cognitive economy, a psychological principle, suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of cognitive science (cs.CC). Finally, the paper's use of learning curves to test and compare representations suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG) or systems and control (cs.SY).
